<DOC><DOCNO> AP890328-0165 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-89 2124EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-28 0574</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0589</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Over Texas; Heat in East</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy thunderstorms gave Texans a drenching on Tuesday whileEastern Seaboard residents got a record-breaking preview of summer.Snow and freezing rain fell in parts of Minnesota and far northernMichigan.   An upper-air disturbance moving across southern Texas producedthe strong thunderstorms that prompted flash flood watches fornortheast Texas, extreme southeast Oklahoma and all of Arkansas.   Rainfall overnight averaged around 3 inches in the Dallas-FortWorth area, with 5 inches falling in northern sections of FortWorth. Rivers and streams rose rapidly.   Up to 4 inches of rain soaked portions of south-central Texas,and over an inch of rain fell in 50 minutes in the town of Hondo.Flooding was reported along Cowhouse Creek at Fort Hood.   Winds from an intense thunderstorm gusted to 58 mph at Austin,Texas, and blew a tree onto a house just west of the capital.   A tornado watch was posted for much of southern and easternTexas.   One to 2 inches of rain drenched western Arkansas, floodinghighways in Sebastian County.   Welcome rains fell over eastern Kansas and western Missouri,with 2 inches falling at Westwood, Kan., and over 1.75 inches atLiberty, Mo.   Northern Minnesota and western upper Michigan had wintryweather, with rain mixed with freezing rain and light snow.   Rain showers fell over central California, western Montana andthe upper Great Lakes. Portions of the Great Lakes were shrouded infog.   A cold front moving through the central Pacific Coast producedhigh winds, including gusts over 70 mph west of Reno, Nev. A highwind warning was in effect for extreme western Nevada.   Record spring warmth continued from the lower Mississippi Valleyto the Atlantic Coast, with temperatures in the 80s as far north assouthern New England.   It was 90 degrees at Baltimore-Washington International Airport,shattering a 44-year-old record. Elsewhere, records were set ortied at Beckley, W.V. (81), Boston, (81), Cape Hatteras, N.C. (76),Huntington, W.V. (86), Mansfield, Ohio (75), Montgomery, Ala. (85),Portland, Maine (67), Providence, R.I. (79), Roanoake, Va. (82) andYoungstown, Ohio (77).   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 88 degrees at McAllen, Texas, andFort Myers, Fla.   The nation's low Tuesday was 17 degrees at Gunnison and Alamosa,Colo.   The forecast for Wednesday called for scattered showers andthunderstorms from eastern portions of the southern plains to muchof the middle and lower Mississippi Valley, the Ohio and Tennesseevalleys, the lower Great Lakes and the middle and northern AtlanticCoast, with thunderstorms most prevalent from eastern Texas to thelower Mississippi Valley and southern portions of the lower OhioValley; rain showers from the Pacific Northwest to the northern andcentral Rockies and the northern plains, with snow over northernMaine and snow mixed with rain at higher elevations of the centralRockies.   High temperatures were expected to be in the 30s from easternNorth Dakota to northern Minnesota, upper Michigan and northernMaine; the 40s and 50s from the northern and central Pacific Coastto the northern and central Intermountain West, the northernRockies, much of the northern Plains, the Great Lakes and northernNew England; the 80s from south central Texas to the Gulf Coast,Florida, and the southern Atlantic Coast, and across southwestTexas and the desert Southwest; and in the 60s and 70s in the restof the nation.</TEXT></DOC>